1⃣5⃣Conclusion

This series of ideas are admittedly speculative, but very much grounded in things that are already happening.

The future is going to be much stranger than we can imagine. For good, or ill, blockchains might play an important role in the upcoming conflicts https://t.co/aA6wfzwR8b

1⃣4⃣Arms for all

Money is becoming political to a level that wasn’t even possible. These were the games of rich and savvy elites, but they’re becoming accessible to all

I don’t know what the world that emerges on the other side of this looks like. But it’ll be interesting! https://t.co/p0rUPQp8i0

1⃣3⃣Blockchains as targets

If #Cardano succeeds in onboarding government data infrastructure on-chain then the blockchains themselves become targets for attack (digital and physical), including the native tokens and the stakepool operators/miners. https://t.co/nZmN8Wpmqp

1⃣2⃣Uncensorable Information

I recently received a tip with a message embedded in the transaction itself, and it got me thinking

This could be used as a means of publicly storing information that is as permanent as the blockchain it’s on. No POV can ever be fully unpersoned now https://t.co/S793zHEUM4

1⃣1⃣Blockchain Diplomacy

Part of the issue with geopolitics is that there’s major counterparty risk

In future, you could put conditions of a ceasefire on a smart contract guarded by oracles. Whoever doesn’t break the agreement is rewarded with money locked inside the contract https://t.co/ZSMEIoRaxd

🔟Leaderless Armies

In Homage to Catalonia, Orwell said that organizing the Republican army was a mess as the horizontal leadership structure didn’t lend itself to being an effective fighting force

Fighting forces structured as DAOs could solve this issue of hierarchy https://t.co/QyQC84yH6D

9⃣Outsourcing Spying

Oracles are a third-party service that connects smart contracts with the outside world, primarily to feed info to crypto from the real world. 

This tech could be used to collect and verify information that is useful for strategic purposes when in a conflict https://t.co/e0E1zHywO2

8⃣Killers for hire

9/Conclusion

Cardano shares commonalities with pineapple pizza

Its glaring differences separate it from the rest of the crowd and make it a target for vitriol

Yet despite this, there's a growing majority that has come to quietly respect it and enjoy it, away from prying eyes https://t.co/WlRTfKKAtX

8/Cardano's objectively good

People don't spend their time fighting something that isn't a threat to their position

And if wallet addresses and activity is anything to go by, people are noticing this as well

There's growing public preference falsification regarding $ADA https://t.co/3R3MoASlEs

7/Disproportionate Hate

Funnily enough, pineapple on pizza is not the most hated/worse topping. That honour goes to Anchovies and Eggplants

In other words, pineapple's visibility is what attracts the hatred

It would not be this loudly disliked were it not a viable alternative https://t.co/6qFMqtmRmO

6/Irony becomes real

Our differences as a blockchain make us a target for mockery and derision

Over time though, people not in on the joke come in and start taking sides for real. So the rivalries become antagonistic instead of tongue in cheek https://t.co/1YOujVG88i

5/Cardano Hate

Much like Pineapple on Pizza, it's become a bit of a meme to hate on Cardano

If you were to put L1 blockchains up in a lineup it's the one that would stand out: goofy/eccentric founder, obsession with peer review, slow to market, aversion to VC funding, etc https://t.co/NJyBgMTjaI

4/What does this have to do with Cardano? 

Due to the lack of financial sophistication of the average crypto investor (partially owing to the lack of balance sheets /income statements of projects), people are primarily convinced to buy things based on what the crowds say https://t.co/1LwJZmNEtA

3/Lies

In pollster terms, this is known as "preference falsification" where one side has perceived their choices as socially undesirable, yet they're happy to express it in private, in a voting booth and their actions

So the vocal side seems dominant when they're not https://t.co/91MWf3IGga

2/Going Deeper

It's become such a social taboo on the Web to mention one likes pineapple pizza that it's rare to see genuine supporters thereof

Curiously, this does not align with the stats, as a majority of people prefer it. https://t.co/zFcSHyExWh

2⃣6⃣Summary

$ADA prides itself on a “measure twice and cut once” approach, and avoids catering to cryptobros, focusing instead on the majority of people who had no reason to get into crypto

It has all the makings of one day being world-spanning data management infrastructure https://t.co/lwT7JymZeq

2⃣5⃣Long Term Thinking

Cardano is one of the few crypto projects that is thinking in decades instead of just until the next update on their roadmap.

If it plays its cards right, it could be around for generations, as I’ve explored before:
https://t.co/uVh8t28ftw

2⃣4⃣Regulation-proof

From the outset, the reason that Cardano had its ICO in Japan, as opposed to the US, was to avoid potential regulatory risks

As such, it has always tried to be on the right side of the authorities. And is likely well-positioned to survive legal scrutiny https://t.co/IAEHa5MOrp

2⃣3⃣Stress-Tested

Cardano understands the risks

It's a fantastic sign that it was able to survive not just the crypto-winter but also rebuild itself in the Byron Reboot and then thrive

I’ve worked with projects that barely survived winter, and they are STILL on life support https://t.co/867zvCzAqV

2⃣2⃣Catalyst

There are projects that might be useful to have, but unprofitable to run (think public lighting)

Most cryptos without a community treasury will have to make do without them, but Cardano can fund these loss leading services without an issue through Catalyst funding https://t.co/sh1yVMTFKJ

2⃣1⃣Self-Governing

ADA is one of the few cryptos that has emphasised community governance in a meaningful way

It’s in the process of creating on-chain voting infrastructure for ALL its native assets https://t.co/MKrHxkgO9T

2⃣0⃣Strong Community

The Cardano community is among one of the most passionate crypto groups out there.

The numbers bear this out, compare social media reach of any of its rivals Ethereum, Solana, Luna, etc and it beats them, or it trades blows favourably https://t.co/LKoO8R0UGF

1⃣9⃣Decentralized-ish

Our Nakamoto Coefficient, the number of entities you need to control to take over #Cardano, is 28

For #Bitcoin, it’s 4 and for #Ethereum, it’s 2

As such, while we could be better in our decentralization efforts, we’re also comparatively quite good. https://t.co/JX16GfAeCR

1⃣8⃣Democratised Programming

Cardano knows that majority of users aren’t Haskell programmers (or any kind of developers) so they’re developing Marlowe

It's a means by which normal people can create and deploy smart contracts -you won’t need to be able to code to create programs https://t.co/pHMbxieEkj

1⃣7⃣Democratised Infrastructure

#Cardano is decentralized because tech-savvy people of modest means (for Western standards) can afford to run a stakepool

This is in stark contrast to Bitcoin, where mining companies are so big that they can get listed on the stock market https://t.co/dnDCO2vTgY

1⃣6⃣Censorship Resistant

It’s entirely possible (and somewhat encouraged) to run a full node wallet on Cardano. And even if one opts not to do that, there are dozens of emerging alternatives

So a centralized entity can’t lock people out of the ecosystem if they’re already in https://t.co/fQihhCHAOi

1⃣5⃣Not VC owned

If a project is controlled by a big entity, they don’t view you as a shareholder. But as a resource to exploit

As we’ve seen with JP Morgan gaining control of Consensys, which controls Metamask (the main wallet in $ETH), chains are subject to political bias https://t.co/1xtxBBL2Jo

1⃣4⃣Completely new business models

This EUTXO system allows for the development of apps that would be unfeasible or horrendously expensive if they were found on other blockchains

An example is @ContactDrip which airdrops millions of tokens weekly to users for modest prices https://t.co/u9aZ6UYOfB

1⃣3⃣EUTXO

$ADA uses an innovative Extended UTXO accounting model to support multi-assets and smart contracts

This simplifies operations and allows 1 transaction to have many beneficiaries. For instance, @anetaBTC has done airdrops with thousands of people at the cost of pennies https://t.co/kFRiRT4Ehc

1⃣2⃣Competitors

Vast majority of rivals are centralized databases; they’re spreadsheets that charge you every time you alter a number. I don’t see much future in these, as we already have better alternatives

Many of its decentralized competitors are having technical challenges https://t.co/lL96PRYdRb

1⃣1⃣Possible Gen 4?

Cardano likes to market itself as a Gen 3 blockchain that has meaningfully addressed the trilemma of scalability, security and decentralization

Not content with that, it’s playing around with becoming a PoW/PoS hybrid and possibly introducing Proof of Merit https://t.co/hRc68rgPDm

🔟Thought Leader

Cardano is a trailblazer, not only were they among the first at-scale PoS blockchains, but other leading projects occasionally borrow from it.

Polkadot, for instance, took principles from Cardano for its own consensus mechanism https://t.co/0OwIFpmp7j

9⃣Pappers

Cardano believes in peer review and open access to data. This grants access to cryptographers, developers, etc who have no interest in being anything other than academics, but are geniuses in their own right

They have already published 131+ research papers https://t.co/yJR8zsgBBo

🎱Difference in Culture

Part of the problem in startups is that founders believe you can just throw brainpower at a problem, and it’ll solve itself

This has some merit when you’re prototyping, but not when you’re trying to build something that will last generations https://t.co/D7DE0cNatm

7⃣Programming Language

While Cardano is often criticized for using Haskell, many of the largest financial entities also use it

It’s not the most intuitive of languages but due to its focus on function instead of objects, there are fewer bugs in the code

https://t.co/PzoHrKUXzv

6⃣Formal protocols

Silicon Valley culture advocates to “move fast and break things” because they assume that the things that will be broken don’t belong to them

On the other hand, Cardano is fastidious in its correctness and thus it’s a very solid base to build from https://t.co/JkMDbhbCFo

5⃣Huge Audience

Given that it’s focusing on real finance and identity, its potential market cap could dwarf entire sectors of the world economy

It’s been estimated that formalizing the property rights of the world's poor could unlock trillions in 'dead capital' by itself https://t.co/WJnKZlGM85

4⃣Real World Use vs Degen

Crypto has a gambling problem, it’s largely not geared towards actually changing the world but instead caters to the existing crypto degens in their mothers’ basements

Cardano is the exception in that it is trying to create real-world apps first https://t.co/75nOCNn7MQ

3⃣Intro

Cardano is the 8th largest blockchain by market cap

It’s been in operation since 2017 and survived threats such as the crypto-winter, and having to rebuild itself as it encountered some early complications

Now it’s said to be the most advanced and robust PoS blockchain https://t.co/TH1Xw1d2Gq

1⃣5⃣Conclusion

Traditional powers will try to restrict capital flight to try to stop their financial ruin. If things get bad enough, the public will use crypto anyway to flee

Eventually, this leads to the creation of new types of money that diffuse power to many separate groups https://t.co/CAQrOdwXKG

1⃣4⃣Community-based money

As the wider public becomes more used to crypto, they will broaden their preferences and begin to accept different types of cash which increases the sources of power in society

Here’s a thread where I discuss it in detail

https://t.co/2jVkovZNaf

1⃣3⃣Rise of Stablecoins

While reserve-based currencies reliant on some central entity were initially the norm, algorithmic stablecoins are becoming more popular

So communities can create stable units of value that they can transact with each other https://t.co/9Pn3GgJvjF

1⃣2⃣Instability of crypto

L1 crypto is good to exit immediate influence of govs & corps, but it’s horrible to try to run a business from - your business costs are utterly unpredictable hour to hour, and you might not even know you’re earning or losing money with any transaction https://t.co/bLbMRtf9IY

1⃣1⃣Cryptos & the Shadow Economy

@IOHK_Charles  has said that in time it’ll become more difficult to track people’s assets, so govs might start switching to taxing stuff that you can’t move but still need - like real estate, or your immediate consumption (via heavier VAT) https://t.co/mk7XNWfvIP

🔟Shadow Economy

Greek politicians have joked that tax avoidance is Greece’s national sport

It’s not uncommon for businesses to have two sets of account books - one you show to family and partners, while another one you show to the taxman. Much of the economy works in secret. https://t.co/f3OlDNSeA3

9⃣Government Crackdowns

Once govs realize that their capital controls aren’t working as intended, they start trying to plug the gaps with overbearing regulation with very harsh penalties and/or draconian taxes.

This might stop most people unless they’re REALLY motivated https://t.co/ecHTyTvVLl

8⃣Not your money

The fact of the matter is that while you play in the ecosystem created by banks and governments, there are enough arcane regulations that they can outright freeze or take your funds.

So it’s not in their interest to allow you to leave, which brings us to… https://t.co/vwdffnVnA2

7⃣Flight to Crypto

It's become increasingly common for countries with capital controls and economic trouble to experience crypto booms, such as in Venezuela, Turkey and Nigeria.

Crypto has a lower barrier to entry than setting bank accounts abroad and evading restrictions https://t.co/q5zSneg96w

6⃣Crypto & Cyprus

Commentators at the time were very surprised by people's flight to crypto, as they dismissed the asset class altogether.

Yet, even so, it was so intense that BTC went up by 176.2% in March 2013 alone! https://t.co/OXGKeHHbi2

5⃣Cyprus bank run CONTD

Some of those who didn’t manage to flee with their funds in crypto effectively got their money confiscated and exchanged for bank shares

This was euphemistically called a “bail-in” rather than being called what it was: theft & coercion https://t.co/a2dv74LTRI

4⃣Cyprus bank run

From 2012-2013, Cyprus banks were in dire straits due to exposure to the Euro debt crisis, and many other bad choices

Daily cash withdrawals were limited to only €300, so people took to buying Bitcoin to flee from the immediate control of the authority's arm https://t.co/OeLrsGdeOR

3⃣Flight to Safety

If the local currencies have lost their appeal, it’s normal that money flees to perceived safe havens like gold, USD, or CHF. But what if those aren’t an option either because there are also issues with them or the exits are shut? https://t.co/2HuU9BVOKD

2⃣Setting the Scene

A way to gain quick legitimacy online is to have the “As seen on MSNBC, etc” badges

1⃣9⃣ SHILLING

If you liked this, please consider giving a follow. I write one large thread a week, which looks at crypto from a completely different POV

I then convert these threads to full-blown articles with greater depth and evidence on Medium
https://t.co/jm5ig4Pc9H

1⃣8⃣CONCLUSION

The enemy isn’t necessarily current multipool owners. They’re acting rationally given the circumstances, but we need to think longer term.

If we are to survive and thrive we must change things on a protocol level! https://t.co/zjPq20oEOU

1⃣7⃣DAVE VS GOLIATH

For now, most multipool operators are still bound by human capacities, someone new can still feasibly compete against what they offer, even with their advantages

Sooner or later though, they’ll be so big that barriers to entry will be insurmountable https://t.co/jDCQQyW9I3

1⃣6⃣ THREATS

If we don’t make it difficult, if not impossible, on a protocol level to have permanent multipools, then eventually giants will come and SPOs won’t be able to compete

What if Google comes in tomorrow and opens 500 pools to saturation? They’re perfectly capable https://t.co/B25NUyGBPC

1⃣5⃣SOLUTIONS?

It needs to be taboo to have permanent multipools, and the community needs to act

More importantly, we need to change things at a protocol level, perhaps even use oracles to identify multipools and penalize them 

Warning from IOHK's Chief scientist Prof Kiayias; https://t.co/c1l7qRoO3d

1⃣4⃣DEVIL'S ADVOCATE

There are multipool operators who genuinely love #Cardano and have done a lot of good with the advantages they’ve accrued

I don’t want them to leave, and I like them, such as @bigpeyYT. They’ve perhaps gotten a bit too greedy but that’s a matter of opinion. https://t.co/ljuuBs9YfG

1⃣3⃣ SILVER LININGS

Multipool operators aren’t evil, and can even provide value

It’s like pollution - they’re a negative externality. Some is worth having as it allows for modern life, other (ie producing disposable plastic items) is not

Too much pollution and we die https://t.co/Sj4su1wW3D

1⃣2⃣ TRAGEDY OF THE COMMONS

Imagine there’s a field and we’re farmers. Everyone can graze their cattle there without limits

The dominant strategy becomes to bring as large of a herd as you can, as everyone else will do the same. The field then dies, same with decentralization https://t.co/7ZG8bLkdk5

1⃣1⃣WHO CARES ABOUT DECENTRALIZATION?

Govs & corps will only move their stuff on #Cardano when they have assurances that a third party can't meddle with it, ergo if you want widespread adoption you need decentralization, otherwise, it's cheaper to use centralized AWS servers https://t.co/htOzJ5fLtl

🔟MULTIPOOL OPERATORS

It is with this backdrop that it becomes heinous when we see people who have done so well that they decide to open several stakepools, thereby enriching themselves at the expense of the wellbeing of the wider community by centralizing the network https://t.co/zxJ2zgkWpl

9⃣ZERO-SUM GAME

Cardano has a fixed max supply of 45bn coins. Meaning that definitionally, if a delegator decides to stake with an SPO, every other SPO is worse off for not having received that stake (unless their stakepool is fully saturated and they don’t open another one) https://t.co/ESprcIxJuO

8⃣RAZOR-THIN MARGINS

Setups vary, and some can do it cheaper, but normally you need several hundred dollars a month to run a stakepool.

So, if you don’t have the delegators to break even, you’re expected to lose money for months on end in the hopes that this might change https://t.co/y3iaesxK4g

7️⃣GIVE ALL OR GO

As $ADA price goes up, and the number of stakepools rises, the barriers to entry increase

To stand out you have to give more to your delegators (time, resources, etc), but given that many SPOs don’t even have enough delegators to keep the lights on, they leave https://t.co/masdRQVj7v

6️⃣WINNER TAKES IT ALL

It's a well-studied phenomenon that in complex systems through random chance there is usually one victor that takes most, as early advantages compound on each other until there are insurmountable barriers. 

The only way to stop it is to change the system https://t.co/IoVtAHp9Fh

5️⃣TOO LATE?

Early SPOs were able to amass fortunes and create competitive advantages as they faced little competition

Imagine when you’re told it’s a fair fight when someone bought in at $0.15 and your entry price is $1.5 but you’re still expected to pledge the same ADA https://t.co/hFat9jbAHe

4️⃣DELEGATOR REWARDS

Users who stake get paid a portion of the reward for minting a block in exchange for their delegation, proportional to their stake. 

Some SPOs have also started trying to create communities and offer additional benefits in the hopes of attracting delegation https://t.co/XIN6g3N4Mg

3️⃣THE IMPORTANCE OF DELEGATORS

The frequency at which SPOs can mint blocks to add to the chain depends on how much stake they have delegated

Normal users (delegators) can vote on who gets blocks with their ADA stake, and the network will divvy blocks out proportional to this https://t.co/EflRNQ6aGb

2️⃣THE BASICS

Cardano is a decentralized computational network, where individuals can choose to become stakepool operators (SPO) and thereby help the system process transaction blocks

In exchange for processing transactions, they receive a reward https://t.co/YMUUgOu3en

1️⃣ASS COVERING

I’m sure this thread will ruffle feathers, I understand that there’s passion on both sides

I don’t want enemies, and I want what’s best for #Cardano

To do this, we must come together and discuss difficult issues civilly 

Please try to keep the discourse polite https://t.co/Jd71s5V5KI

CONCLUSION

We’ve been looking at NFTs and memecoins wrong - they’re not traditional assets

They’re tokenized units of culture, deriving value from people participating in their communities - through them, owners feel like they belong to something

Culture's going decentralized! https://t.co/3MEdJzRfV2

1⃣1⃣ACTIVE VS PASSIVE

For hundreds of years, the wider public has been a spectator in the production of culture and communities. But NFTs and Memecoins are the first indications that it's changing

Audiences can now create (and financially benefit) from their creative pursuits https://t.co/ctNyJH4TOl

🔟DECENTRALIZATION OF CULTURE

When stories were told by the campfire, generating culture was communal. The legends changed with each retelling and every storyteller

We then lost this and concentrated culture into a handful of people, but a decentralized culture’s coming back https://t.co/3SlTHbmjom

9⃣INVOLVEMENT

The difference between earlier fandoms and this new style of groups is that they don't consider fan involvement a nuisance and legal headache 

Fans are even encouraged to participate, as these projects can't exist without derivative work done by passionate people https://t.co/FG529SR7Np

8⃣COMMUNITY

A shitpost I once read made a great point

“Grown men are afraid of selling their million-dollar monkey pics because they’re afraid of losing the friendship of others like them”

Absurd?

Think of it not as an asset, but a country club membership and it makes sense https://t.co/BjAuFkXG3f

7⃣FAN TOKENS

They’re an NFT/Memecoin hybrid. They’re tokens for fans of a sports team, which might give you special privileges for owning them, like access to tickets, cheaper merch, etc

They can also allow you to get involved in picking the team’s uniforms https://t.co/iq9Fzr9fWq

6⃣PURPOSE

I used to dismiss meme coins & NFTs - mind you, I’m still sceptical of them

But I was missing the point, they’re primarily social signifiers of belonging to a group! They’re closer to a football jersey than an investment https://t.co/LXmtlV2QLd

5⃣ CONTD

We’re taking abstract concepts that would’ve otherwise been impossible to keep track of, like a community’s desirability, and making them tradable assets

When a meme coin/NFT is sold, it’s really a referendum where people are asked “how much is this community worth?” https://t.co/jY751wJkec

4⃣TOKENIZATION OF IDEAS

Fiat Money (as we know it) is a concept we agreed on to tokenize the abstract notions of what we considered to be valuable in society

Crypto is allowing us to tokenize many other abstract concepts, like virality, community, etc

https://t.co/1t6zG8doeS

3⃣WHAT IS AN NFT?

NFTs, while having vast future applications, are now primarily JPEGs. Well, not even that. They’re links on the blockchain, which point to a photo off-chain

There are entire communities of NFT collectors who proudly display their collections on social media https://t.co/qK6DubqiMa

2⃣WHAT IS A MEME COIN?

Crypto assets that often have no utility, or are just blatant rebrandings of already existing projects.

The key strength of a meme coin is its community, as the price soars when it is the talk of the town and crashes otherwise https://t.co/Lsxq1XZAw9

1⃣ WHAT IS A MEME?

The term first came to use by biology professor Richard Dawkins to signify that evolution doesn’t solely exist in the realm of genetics, but also in ideas - they can be shared, or go extinct

Memes are ideas that get passed on and mutate when transmitted https://t.co/Z6VPB0vgoU

Conclusion

Hopefully, these strategies allow you to capitalize on the insane volatility endemic in crypto rather than be hit by them

Don't FOMO in, decide to buy things at a certain price months in advance, and with this move you can invest without stress and on autopilot https://t.co/ozFLT5NJB8

This "bear trap" strategy has the benefit of working with the inevitable system outages that the CEX experience with the increase in volatility.

Not only that, but you can get "flash crashes" where the prices were only available for a handful of minutes, and you get 'em 6/n https://t.co/QCHXEYz2Ab

A note on prices...

People have a bias towards certain numbers, you can see this in the order books, anything ending in 0 or 5 are often support areas, as people default to them.

So set your buy orders for weird numbers like ending in 3 or 7 to get ahead of the rest

5/n https://t.co/xlrkQIAt2n

You can also DCA backwards by creating a descending ladder - say one buy order at $0.85, another at $0.80, etc.

Absolute worst-case scenario you didn't manage to buy all of them, but you got many of the best prices and you kept your money. 

3/n https://t.co/2J3lwq2yzW

Really lowball, don't be shy and treat it as if that money is gone and you drank it away (if you're anywhere near needing it in the next months, cancel the orders and use the money)

The buy order prices should be ones you'd feel VERY happy to get when you place the orders. 2/n https://t.co/vNqnYE8ZKJ
